hands_on_practices.problem:
According to the Fundamental Theorem of Finite Abelian Groups, any finite abelian group is isomorphic to a direct product of cyclic groups whose orders are prime powers. These prime-power orders are known as the elementary divisors of the group. A complete set of elementary divisors, disregarding their order, uniquely determines the group up to isomorphism.

Consider the following sets of integers. Which one of these sets CANNOT represent the collection of elementary divisors for any finite abelian group?

A. {4, 9, 25}

B. {8, 3, 3, 5}

C. {2, 2, 2, 9, 5}

D. {4, 6, 25}

E. {4, 2, 5, 5}
